XPO Logistics terminal NML experienced a UN3109 TBHP-70-AQ release from a 5-gallon jerrican due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and advised terminal personnel had already conducted cleanup and placed the damaged jug and impacted absorbents into a closed top poly drum. The crew removed the damaged jug from the drum and placed it into a 55-gallon vented poly drum, confirming 1-gallon released. The impacted drum was then cut up and containerized along with the impacted absorbents into a separate 55-gallon vented poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XTM experienced an over the road release of UN1760 Biocide 4 from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released to a 23' x 5' area of the trailer floor and a 50’ x 2’ area of the gravel lot below due to a puncture caused by a broken pallet. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Floor dry and a citric acid solution were then deployed and utilized to clean the impacted areas. The impacted gravel was shoveled up and the area pH came back at a 7 once all contaminants were removed. All impacted gravel and absorbents were containerized into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Tomah, WI and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal XSG experienced a UN3103 TBPB release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors for containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-cup of product released to the box only due to the vented cap releasing as a result of load shift. The jugs were removed from the impacted box and wiped down for shipment on. The impacted cardboard was neutralized with water and containerized along with the impacted rags and PPE into a vented 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XCH experienced an over the road release of UN3265 DC14 from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to a 15' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 10' x 5' area on the concrete roadway due to a drum being tipped over in transit, causing a release from the loose bung cap. Three drums were up righted, wiped down, and secured for shipment on. Lime and absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas to neutralize and clean the release. All impacted absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Chicago Heights, IL and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: NUMEROUS PACKAGES WERE COLD TO THE TOUCH AND HAD FROST FORMING ON THE OUTSIDE. THESE PACKAGES WERE MIXED IN WITH PACKAGES FROM THE SAME SHIPPER THAT WERE PROPERLY MARKED AS CONTAINING DRY ICE. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE NON-MARKED DRY ICE PACKAGES, WE FOUND APPROXIMATELY NINE KILOGRAMS OF DRY ICE COOLING DOG FOOD IN EACH BOX. THESE THIRTY BOXES ARE MISSING DRY ICE MARKINGS ON THE OUTER BOXES. THE PACKAGES ARE GOING TO VARIOUS CONSIGNEES IN THE USA. THESE PACKAGES HAVE NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO. THESE PACKAGES WERE SHIPPED USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER B37A21, PETCO-JFFD AMERICOLD, 34 FAIRMONT CITY BLVD., NATIONAL STOCK YARDS IL 62071.

XPO Logistics terminal XKC experienced a UN3266 Enrich No. 299 release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-ounces of product released to the drum lid due to the drum being dropped, causing a puncture. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. All impacted rags used to clean the release were placed into a 5-gallon poly pail. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal LTU experienced a UN1791 Extract-2 release from (2) 55-gallon poly drums. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-cups of product released to the drum lids of each drum due to loose bung caps. The released product was cleaned off the drums with absorbent rags and the caps were re-secured for shipment on. All impacted absorbent pads and PPE were containerized into a 45-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On October 2, 2023, four (4) 55-gallon drums of UN3093 arrived without caps and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EX Environmental (EXE) to remediate the impacted site. Three of the lids were re-secured and the facility had to provide a fourth. The drums were sent back with the driver. EXE personnel deployed absorbents and absorbent pads to the ferric nitrate solution-impacted trailer interior. All spent absorbent pads and absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport to the terminal.

column168: A FULLY LABELED HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY AN UNLOADER IN UNLOAD C THAT APPEARED TO BE WET AND STAINED ON THE OUTER CARTON. THE UNLOADER VACATED THE AREA, NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR AND A DMP RESPONDER ARRIVED WITHIN 5 MINUTES DONNING THE PROPPER PPE. FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND CORRECT RESPONSE SHEET, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OUTSIDE OF THE CARTON AND THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, ONE OF THE INNER VESSELS WAS FOUND TO HAVE A LOOSE CAP BY 3/4 OF A TURN AND APPROXIMATELY 3 OUNCES OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED AND LEAKED ONTO THE OUTER CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLE WALL 120 POUND CAPACITY FIBERBOARD BOX.

The impacted absorbents were then containerized into a 20-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On October 8, 2023, one (1) 50-pound bag of UN1487 was damaged during transit and released approximately one (1) cup of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from  First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. On October 9, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3098 was punctured and released approximately 467-gallons of product to the trailer interior, lift gate, and asphalt roadway. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to remediate the impacted site. AS personnel utilized a vacuum pump to transfer the undamaged product from the damaged tote to a new tote and secured for normal transport. Crews then deployed additional granular absorbent and a neutralizing agent to the impacted trailer floor, lift gate and asphalt roadway and worked them in utilizing hand tools. All UN3098 impacted material, including the damaged tote, was collected and containerized in nine (9) 55-gallon drums and were taken to  RLC-SJE to be staged and added to the facility waste stream. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date for pressure washing of impacted asphalt and monitor waste at RLC-SJE.  On Oct 11, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. The waste was still reacting and drums were left unsealed in an open trailer. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date to continue monitoring the waste at RLC-SJE.  On Oct 12, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. There was olfactory evidence that the waste was still reacting and drums were left unsealed in an open trailer. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date to continue monitoring the waste at RLC-SJE.  On Oct 13, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. The reaction had ceased. The impacted trailer was re-inspected and it was confirmed that no further remediation necessary at the direction of RLC personnel. AS personnel secured the site and scheduled to return at a later date to secure the waste at RLC-SJE to be added to the facility waste stream.  On Oct 16, 2023, AS personnel arrived on-site at RLC-SJE and inspected six (6) 55-gallon drums containing UN3098 impacted material. The reaction had ceased and drums were secured. RLC personnel took possession of nine (9) 55-gallon drums of waste to be added to the facility waste stream.

On October 9, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1993 was crushed during transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel collected one (1) damaged 5-gallon pail of UN1993 for disposal. Crews then deployed granular absorbent to the impacted trailer floor and worked them in utilizing hand tools. Once collected, TLE personnel utilized a degreasing agent with absorbent wipes to collect any residual product. The undamaged freight was re-secured for normal transport. All UN1993 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal by R+L.

SequenceEvent: Pile of Ecolab hazmat packages found 5:30pm on Trailer 954036 from 755 MESQ on Door 82 of the small unload. Plastic 5 gallon drum of Ecolab Built Detergent was found upside down and when placed upright it was discovered lid seal was leaking. The package was placed in a lined red tote and removed from operations posthaste. DescribePack: Lid seal consistently leaking on all sides of the packaging. The drum was found upside down, suggesting internal corrosion of the inner seal. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PPE donned. Package and spillage were placed in a lined and lidded red tote for transport to the HMPA. Care was taken to separate this hazmat from another leaking hazmat of Sodium hypochlorite solution within the same trailer.

SequenceEvent: Package was inbound scanned at 0433. At approximately 0510 QA was called to unload managers desk by baydoor 12. QA was notified that HazMat package appeared to be leaking and that their was a strong smell emanating from package. Upon inspection it was found that one of the two items in the package had a loose top that allowed some of its inner contents to spill out. HazMat was placed in a salvage drum and moved to QA1 to process post sort. DescribePack: 2 items were found in the package. 1 was a gallon of paint and the other was a gallon of paint thinner. The lid on the can of paint thinner was loose and allowed some of its contents to spill out. Lower right corner of outer packaging appears to have a regangle shaped wet mark of about 3 x 5 inches. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: As soon as QA identified that the package was indeed a damaged HazMat the item was placed in a salvage drum, picked up from the unload and brought to QA1 to be processed post sort.

column168: On 10/20/23 at aproximately 1230, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 563935 to the station location in Irving, reporting an undeclared hazardous substance shipment.  The shipment consists for eight fiberboard boxes, each containing one plastic jerrican labeled "Champignon Liquid" from China.  The shipment emitted an odor, warranting further investigation.  An online sds of a similar product revealed that the commodity is classifed as UN 3082.  The shipment was not prepared in accordanace with IATA Regulations, having shipped without the requires markings, labeling, packaging and paperwork.  The complete shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the impacted site.  Union Pacific (UP) personnel would not allow any third-party contractors on-site without prior approval. At approximately 8:15 PM CDT, a crew from GES arrived on-site and were instructed to remain on standby until further notice. It was later determined that GES personnel would not be authorized to make entry onto UP property and any remediation would be handled by another party retained by UP. CES and GES were advised to stand down by Mr. Judah.

Crews utilized an 85-gallon open top drum to overpack and contain the damaged 55-gallon drum. ME personnel utilized absorbent pads to collect the released product from the impacted areas. Crews removed two damaged boards from the impacted pallet, and returned the salvaged pallet to R+L. All Loctite Frekote PMC (UN1993) impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum, and the previously mentioned 85-gallon overpack, and R+L personnel took possession of the waste to be added to the facility waste stream.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported tank car GATX73831 leaking from the top of the car.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the leak was found to be from the liquid valve blind flange.  The leak resulted from a defective blind flange gasket and product leaking past the closed liquid line valve.  A new blind flange gasket was installed and the leak stopped.  The shipper was notified and is arranging for a certified mobile shop to replace the valve.

column168: Responded to report of Nitric acid leak from tank car GATX220384 in Brosnan Yard Macon GA. Upon inspection by a contractor, the leak was coming from the liquid line valve. The liquid line valve was in closed position but product was leaking past the valve and the secondary closure cam lock cap. The cam Lock cap was missing a gasket. A gasket was installed for the cap and 4psi of pressure was scrubbed off of the tank car. The leak was stopped. The car will be held pending transfer of load.

On October 11, 2023, three (3) 48-pound boxes of UN3262 were damaged by a forklift and released approximately ten (10) pounds of product to the loading dock floor and pallets. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized a HEPA filter drum vacuum to remove the free-standing product from the impacted area. Cleaners and absorbent pads were utilized to remove any residual product. The damaged boxes and all UN3262 impacted materials and spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 95-gallon drum for disposal purposes. The undamaged cargo was wiped down and repalletized for continued processing and shipping.

column168: Driver had 4000 gals of DEI in the 1st Compartment, and was moving to the next Compartment where he checked the hose and cam locks which were good. The second he pulled the internal valve, it blew a cam lock off the side of Compartment 3. Estimates 5 to 10 gallons of Diesel spilled onto the cement. column169: This was a result of equipment failure from a worn out fitting.  Proper maintenance protocols were followed, and more research is ongoing in to the what can be done to inspect equipment more thoroughly and replace worn out fittings on a more regular time schedule.

SequenceEvent: The hazmat was transported to the van line on a cart. When the package handler lifted the box, it slipped out of his grip and fell to the floor. The inner glass cracked, then broke and leaked the acetone out of the bottle. The package handler immediately notified QA who got absorbent materials and mopped up the spilled acetone using rubber gloves and a plastic container for disposal. The box was placed inside a plastic hazmat red container and brought to the hazmat cage for the HESS report to be completed. DescribePack: The hazmat had one of the glass liter containers break. The container had molded reconstituted paper as liners to keep the glass containers safe. However, there was 3 inches of empty space on the top of the container. This left movement for the glass containers to move around inside the fiberboard box. If the box had 1 1/2" foam on the top of the box and 1 1/2 " foam on the bottom of the box, the bottles would have been secure and safer. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: When the inner glass cracked, then broke and leaked the acetone out of the bottle, the package handler immediately notified QA who got absorbent materials and mopped up the spilled acetone using rubber gloves and a plastic container for disposal. The box was placed inside a plastic hazmat red container and brought to the hazmat cage for the HESS report to be completed.

column168: Driver stated he went into the store to obtain a veeder reading.  Driver did state, the load amount was 3000 gallons per delmo but dialed it back.  Driver stated at first, he didn’t stick diesel tank but stuck the gas drop. Then he mentioned stick was broke and couldn’t get an accurate amount in diesel tank and mentioned he did stick the tank. Driver states he started dropping diesel and then hooked up Unleaded and started to drop it also.  Driver observed diesel not flowing and started gas while trying to figure out problem with diesel.  Driver had to stop diesel flow several times to allow tank to breathe and lifted drop gun off fitting in ground allowing it to drain down.  Driver completed unleaded drop and was clearing hose when he seen product coming from drop.  Driver cleaned up with spill pads.  Driver reported to store but left scene with cones around spill to later return and put down oil dry to finish cleanup.
column169: Supervisor is assigning the driver to be with an instructor for training on loading/ unloading procedures.  Supervisor provided other training and notifications on reporting along with insstructor enforcing policy and procedure requirement for proper reporting and when a driver is released from a scene.  Coach Driver on Training on entering store to access their system and strapping charts.  Driver needs training on pre-trip inspections and inspections on all equipment pertaining to the driver’s job duties.

column168: Forklift blade strike
Forklift Blade Strike

On October 16, 2023, Aerolinahs Brasileiras S.A.’s (DBA LATAM Cargo Brasil, formerly TAM Cargo) flight 8473 departed from Miami International Airport. Approximately 30 minutes after takeoff, the flight returned to Miami International Airport due to the detection of a strong chemical smell from the Main Deck.     2. Cargo Area Inspection:     Upon the flight's return to Miami International Airport, the Miami Dade Fire Department was called to investigate the situation. They requested that the Main Deck be opened to ventilate the area and check for any potential leakage of dangerous goods.     3. Identification of the Chemical:     During the inspection, a pallet in position 2R was identified to contain RFL UN1089 Acetaldehyde. This pallet was promptly removed from its position for further examination. It was later determined that there was no spill of the substance either on the pallet or on the floor of the aircraft.     4. Safety Measures and Gas Dissipation:     Following the removal of the pallet, the Miami Dade Fire Department allowed the aircraft to remain open for approximately 30 minutes to ensure proper ventilation and to monitor the situation. After this time, the Fire Department’s team conducted a cargo inspection and, having found no further issues, cleared the plane for operation. The pallet involved in the incident was isolated for an additional 40 minutes to allow any lingering gases to dissipate, making it safe for handling.     5. Preliminary Investigation Findings:     During the preliminary investigation, it was confirmed that all procedures for handling dangerous goods were followed correctly. While there may have been a partial smell of non-toxic gas, it was determined that the packaging containing the Acetaldehyde was not damaged, and therefore, it did not pose a safety risk.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental (GE) to remediate the impacted site. column168: On October 19, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN2014 was damaged in transit and released approximately 275-gallons of product to the trailer floor and concrete beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized hand tools to collect and containerize all free-standing product and previously deployed absorbents from the trailer floor into five (5) 55-gallon open top drums. HCE personnel utilized a forklift to perform a gravity transfer of the remaining UN2014 in the tote into one (1) additional 55-gallon open top drum. All UN2014-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. The impacted wood pallets were staged on site along with the seven (7) previously generated 55-gallon drums for further management.

column168: Pallet of 4 x 55 gallon steel drums were being removed from a van trailer. When the forklift operator went to back out of the trailer, the pallet failed due to the weight of the drums. When the pallet broke, 1 of the drums tipped against the wall of the trailer and liquid started leaking out of from the ring of the lid. Roughly 2.5 gallons leaked out into the trailer for a period of about 30 seconds. The warehouse associate was able to upright the drum and the leak stopped. Forklift operator and warehouse associate placed spill pads on the floor and soaked up the free liquids, and wiped down the back of the trailer. Upon further inspection of the drum, the lid was removed and revealed that it did not contain a gasket.
column169: -Training Drivers to visually check the pallets that our customers are using/providing making sure they are in good condition for the items they are placing on them. -We will be communicating to all our customers that if we are picking up liquids in an open top drums that they must have the gaskets in place.  -Refresher training for forklift operators to look for damaged pallets prior to moving them.

column168: On 10/01/2023, at 0431 hours, personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered SHQX 51000, a residue tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gases, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Maryland Department of the Environment were notified.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the B-End liquid valve and vapor valve partially open and the secondary closure plugs improperly installed resulting in an active release of lading. The issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Derek Campbell of Kiros Energy, phone 403.483.1250. Contractor personnel closed both open valves and properly installed the secondary closure plugs in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 119 NARRI: 90

column168: On 10/31/2023, at 0959 hours, personnel in the CSXT Radnor Yard discovered GATX5945, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from top of the car. column168: The tanker had been picked up from a 3rd party tanker cleaning company. The investigation revealed that during the cleanout the 3rd party had removed the cleanout port cap on top of the tanker and didn't fully secure the cap once the tanker was cleaned out.  The tanker was then sent to pickup a load at PPG Industries, the driver only checked the top hatch and hose valves after loading.  Upon leaving the shipping facility the driver stopped at a scale 40 miles away, there was no evidence at this time of any release.  Upon reaching his final destination he noticed material had sprayed out of the top of the tanker from the top of the tanker from the cleanout port.  The cap was still affixed but he was able to hand tighten it.  Based upon scale tickets from the beginning and end of his trip we were able to determine the amount that had released 45lbs = 5 gallons. The tanker showed signs of the material spraying onto the top portion of tanker.
column169: Information sharing and additional training. Ensuring that drivers check all openings on a tanker after loading and unloading. Tankers coming back from a cleanout will undergo a through evaluation of all fittings.

column168: On October 11, 2023 at 11:45 during a joint Mechanical inspection with FRA at  the Conrail Pavonia Terminal  PROX 280095 a residue tank car of acetone dripping from the bottom outlet valve of the tank car. Upon inspection it was found that the bottom outlet valve was partially open and the closure pin was not in place. The valve was closed and the pin was replaced in the retainer thus stopping the leak. Marion Environmental, an approved Conrail Contractor was notified to respond, inspect and secure the tank car. Marion personnel, removed the bottom outlet cap and drained the product below the valve. They also found both the liquid and vapor valve secondary plugs less than tool tight. Once the tank car was secured it was released to transportation.  FRA Hazardous Material Inspector, Joe Bowen made notifications to both the Shipper and Consignee of the incident.  Cause Code:  2 x ( 4 + 3 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 0 ) = 28

column168: A Veolia employee at Veolia's ten-day intransit facility in Fremont, CA was moving two 55 gal drums to load onto a trailer with a forklift. The forklift had a double drum attachment which was used to pick up and move the drums. The employee raised the forklift but he failed to lift the drums high enough which resulted in one of the drum being smashed between the drum attachment stabilizing bar and the trailer floor frame. This resulted in one of the drums being crushed and causing a leak. Another employee got on the forklift and quickly brought the drums down to the ground and disengaged the drum grabber so that the drum could be tilted to the side to minimize the spill. Other Veolia employees quickly grabbed absorbent and contained the spill. The damaged drum was placed into an 85 gal poly salvage drum and absorbent was used to cleaned the area.  Pressure washer was used to decontaminated the affected area. The spilled occurred on asphalt and did not result in release to the environment.
column169: Following the incident, an investigation was completed and resulted in the employee involved with the incident being terminated from employment with Veolia. In addition, the EHS manager spoke with all forklift operators on 10/17/23 to retrain in regards to the cause of this incident.

column168: On 10/31/2023, hidden dangerous goods were discovered during the shipment inspection process at the DHL BKL Service Center, 653 East 56th St., Brooklyn, NY 11203.   Transportation by road has been confirmed.

Univar Solutions Driver went to load a tanker at Associated Asphalt with Caustic Soda 50% at 8:30AM on October 11th. Driver failed to recognize seal on external valve of tanker indicating tanker was filled, and failed to check dome gasket because of visibility. Driver arrived at Associated Asphalt, inputted his load number with specific weights, and popped the dome gasket. Loading then began and once the control arm hit 21,0001bs the tanker began to overfill. Driver hit the stopfill button once he noticed that product was coming over the top, but 25-30 gallons of product was released onto the asphalt. Associated Asphalt workers and driver cleaned up spill with spill pads and sorb-oil. NRC clean up company has been contracted to take care of any leftover product on asphalt ground to prevent any residues flowing to retention pond. No injuries.
column169: Driver has been re-trained. A new system for tracking full and empty trailers will be implemented.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 10/10/2023, at 1754 hours, personnel in the CSXT New Johnsonville, Tennessee Yard discovered GATX5945, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Veolia, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2023-10-10-00231). Marion Environmental Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a pressure relief vent with a blown rupture.  While replacing the rupture disc on the car, contractor personnel also determined that the pressure relief device was not equipped with the required hydraulic surge protection.  Contractor personnel removed the blown rupture disk and installed a new 2” SS 165 psi rupture disk, decontaminated the exterior of the tank car to ensure no hazardous residue was present as a result of the release, and remediated the environmental impact to the track area. All issues identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Jeff Humphries. As a result of this release, a CSX employee was splashed with liquid was released from the car during normal switching operations. The employee was able to removing the impacted clothing and decontaminate themselves; the employee refused any medical treatment.

column168: Aircraft was being boarded when passenger sitting in seat 16C noticed smoke coming from their fanny pack. They stood up but could not exit the aircraft because passengers were still boarding and isle way was congested. Passenger passed the fanny pack to other passengers until the fanny pack was thrown in the jetway and doused with water by a deadhead flight attendant. When smoking had ceased and device was cooled down, it was removed. Flight continued to board and departed. Photos upon request.

We conducted a test purchase of Ten Aces Medical Adhesive; a flammable aerosol product. As we suspected, the bottle was improperly packaged and it was not marked as a hazardous shipment. The bottle was shipped via USPS Ground Advantage(9400 1082 0549 9385 6823 17) Shipper did not use a strong outer box; it was shipped in a bubble mailer. Shipper did not use Limited Quantity labels. Shiper did not use Orientation labels. Shipper did not use a plastic bag and absorbant material(USPS requirement). Shipper did not declare the parcel contains a hazardous item(USPS requirement) Note that Ten Aces Medical also ships larger quantities, and international air shipments. We are concerned because Ten Aces Medical appears to operate with a general disregard for DOT regulations, FDA
